Just tell the story…

Just the TWO OF US. I loooove this man with my whole heart. 

If you’re looking for a perfect marriage, it ain’t us. If you’re looking for a marriage that has been challenged, refined, and has stood the test of “for better, for worse” — I’m proud to say it’s us. With each others flaws and all, I can honestly say we love each other more now that we’ve seen the good, bad, and ugly. 

There isn’t anything pretty about the cross, except for the fact that it speaks of a love so deep that nothing can separate us from the Fathers Love… Salvation, Security, Safety, Forgiveness, Grace, Strength— lies beneath the blood that was shed, the nails that were pierced, the bruising and beating, that led to a our eternal security— SALVATION. The ugliest parts of us were forgiven and made new through the most gutting and painful act of SACRIFICE. 

The beauty in marriage isn’t the perfection of it- it’s quite opposite. The power and beauty of marriage is that there is a love so deep for the other, that NOTHING can separate the covenant. It’s easy to say “I do” to the pretty things— but it’s hard to keep saying “ I do” when you now experience the exposure of sin in another, especially when the sin is close, not a distant sin. When the sin directly impacts YOU, it seems easiest to run away. 
But within marriage, there must be a constant reminder that it isn’t about YOU. It is a love so selfless— that as each person is made aware of the others flaws, you learn to embrace not as a burden, but as a call and opportunity to allow the other to see what love and Grace look like first hand. 
The hardest call for humanity. 
— Loving despite. Forgiving despite. Showing up despite. Selflessness despite. Serving despite. Honesty despite. Purity despite. Protecting despite. 

Complete opposite of our wiring as selfish humans. 

I love that Robert and I are called to each other DESPITE. 
The romance is alive, the love runs deep, my love and my soulmate. So grateful we are in this thing!

A close of a chapter, and the start of a new one — 
Yesterday we CLOSED ON SDHQ!!!!!! (Can’t wait to share the journey) 

We are in awe of Gods goodness. Cannot believe we are HERE. Just this time last year we moved into a small office space that would allow our team to meet- a team of roughly 4-6 people. We quickly outgrew this with the demand of the growth of social and the expansion of our team— we desperately needed SPACE. Little did we know God was preparing a space for us located in the Cedars of Dallas. 

After we closed yesterday, we walked into the SDHQ, where team had prepared the space for us— tons of photos from day 1 at Granada when it was just Social Night, from Hi-Fi- to Gilleys— and all the memories that we hold close to our hearts… posted on the wall that we now OFFICIALLY call Home— this space is where we will dream together, serve together, create together, continue to build together. We cried and cried, and dedicated SDHQ to the Lord. His doing, His timing, His way. We are living in our best days, and the good news, our best days are ahead. LOOKING BEHIND— HE HAS BEEN SO GOOD. 

HERE AND NOW— HE IS SO GOOD. 

LOOKING AHEAD— HE WILL FOREVER BE GOOD. 

This is all for Him… grateful we get to participate and play a role in what He is doing in the earth. 

@social_dallas — WE GET TO DO THIS— 

House of Prayer
House of Presence
House for People 

Let’s build!

I love how God goes before us. Always. There isn’t a moment that He isn’t watching, adjusting, going before, closing doors that no man can open, opening doors that no man can shut. He invites us to sit in frustration to drive us into our true freedom. For what we find as free, sometimes keeps us bound. So He calls us to seasons of pain, suffering, discomfort, heartbreak,  betrayal, darkness… to expose the things that sit as savior in our lives. There is only one Savior, and His name is Jesus. 
I share this from my own personal journey. We often have a hard time receiving from those who haven’t walked our path. I may have not walked your road of suffering, but I do know my suffering. 
The commonality we share is our need for the Savior to rescue us from us. 
We need Him to repair the broken parts. 

Suffering isn’t a one time thing. Life is full of moments that catch us off guard, and leave us unsettled within ourselves, and yet, after great suffering, sits great restoration. 

This photo is a moment of Gods kindness towards us. What you see in this photo is not necessarily what we see. 
We see a kiss from Heaven saying - “I’ve always been with you, and I’ll never leave you. I am the God who sees, who is intentional, and who provides redemption to those who accept it.”

Robert and I had the most crushing season of our lives in 2020. The pain and healing was so deep that we couldn’t see beyond, and yet, we were carried beyond our natural ability to overcome. 2020 was year 8 in our marriage. So once we began to walk out God working all things together for our good, we went to get an 8 tattoo, that also represented INFINITY. We were marked by year 8, and the crushing prepared us for that days we are living in now. I can say, we are better, stronger, wiser, and love deeper than ever. 
We pulled up to this resort with weary souls last week, needing God to fill us with His strength. As we pulled up, this infinity sign greeted us. A tiny yet big detail that HE IS WITH US. He always has and always will. When it felt like we wouldn’t get through, we not only got through, we wouldn’t be who we are today without what we conquered together. Tis so sweet to trust in Jesus.
